To attach a screenshot to Allure report for each step in Java, you can follow the steps below:

1. Capture the screenshot of the current screen using any standard Java screenshot library (e.g. Selenium WebDriver, Robot class).

2. Encode the screenshot into a Base64 string using `Base64` library.

3. Create an Allure attachment file with the encoded Base64 string and file type (e.g. PNG)

4. Add the attachment to the current Allure step by adding the file path to `@Attachment` annotation.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to attach a screenshot to Allure report for each step:

```
import io.qameta.allure.Allure;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.OutputType;
import org.openqa.selenium.TakesScreenshot;
import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
import java.util.Base64;

public class ScreenshotUtils {

    public static void takeScreenshot(WebDriver driver) {
        try {
            byte[] screenshot = ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(OutputType.BYTES);
            ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
            baos.writeBytes(screenshot);
            String attachmentName = "Screenshot_" + System.currentTimeMillis();
            Allure.addAttachment(attachmentName, "image/png", baos.toByteArray(), "png");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we first capture the screenshot using `TakesScreenshot` interface from `WebDriver` class, and then encode it into a Base64 string using `Base64` library. 

We then create an Allure attachment file with the encoded Base64 string and file type (which is 'png' in this case), and add it to the current step using `Allure.addAttachment()` method which takes the attachment name, content type, file content and file extension as arguments.

You can then call this method wherever you want to capture a screenshot and attach it to the Allure report in your test. For example:

```
@Test
public void testLogin() {
    // some test steps here
    ScreenshotUtils.takeScreenshot(driver);
    // some more test steps here
    ScreenshotUtils.takeScreenshot(driver);
    // some more test steps here
}
```

In this test method, we call `takeScreenshot()` method from `ScreenshotUtils` class after few test steps to capture a screenshot and attach it to the Allure report for each step.

To create a TestNG listener to capture and attach screenshots to Allure report for each step, you can create a custom listener class and implement the `ISuiteListener`, `ITestListener`, and `ISuiteListener` interfaces. Then, you can override the methods of those interfaces in the listener class to capture and attach screenshots at appropriate times.

Here is an example code snippet for creating the TestNG listener:

```
import io.qameta.allure.Allure;
import org.openqa.selenium.OutputType;
import org.openqa.selenium.TakesScreenshot;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.testng.*;

import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;

public class ScreenshotListener implements ISuiteListener, ITestListener, IInvokedMethodListener {

    public void beforeInvocation(IInvokedMethod method, ITestResult testResult) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void afterInvocation(IInvokedMethod method, ITestResult testResult) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onStart(ISuite suite) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onFinish(ISuite suite) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onTestStart(ITestResult result) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onTestSuccess(ITestResult result) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onTestFailure(ITestResult result) {
        captureScreenshot(result.getMethod().getMethodName(), result.getTestContext().getAttribute("WebDriver"));
    }

    public void onTestSkipped(ITestResult result) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onTestFailedButWithinSuccessPercentage(ITestResult result) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onStart(ITestContext context) {
        // do nothing
    }

    public void onFinish(ITestContext context) {
        // do nothing
    }

    private void captureScreenshot(String methodName, Object driverObject) {
        WebDriver driver = (WebDriver) driverObject;

        try {
            byte[] screenshot = ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(OutputType.BYTES);
            ByteArrayOutputStream baos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
            baos.writeBytes(screenshot);
            String attachmentName = methodName + "_" + System.currentTimeMillis();
            Allure.addAttachment(attachmentName, "image/png", baos.toByteArray(), "png");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

In this listener class, we override methods of the `ISuiteListener`, `ITestListener`, and `IInvokedMethodListener` interfaces to capture screenshots at appropriate times. 

`beforeInvocation` and `afterInvocation` methods are not needed for this implementation and are left empty.

We capture the screenshot in the `captureScreenshot` method which accepts the name of the test method and the `driverObject` as parameters. We then create an Allure attachment file with the encoded Base64 string and file type (which is 'png' in this case), and add it to the current step using `Allure.addAttachment()` method which takes the attachment name, content type, file content and file extension as arguments.

In `onTestFailure` method, we call `captureScreenshot` method to capture a screenshot and attach it to the Allure report on test failures.

Finally, we need to add this listener class to the TestNG test suite. This can be done by specifying the listener class in the testng.xml file:

```
<!DOCTYPE suite SYSTEM "http://testng.org/testng-1.0.dtd" >
<suite name="Allure Test Suite" verbose="1" parallel="tests" thread-count="2" >
    <listeners>
        <listener class-name="com.example.ScreenshotListener"/>
    </listeners>
    <test name="Allure Test">
        <classes>
            <!-- add your test classes here -->
        </classes>
    </test>
</suite>
```

In this `testng.xml` file, we specify the listener class in the `<listeners>` section. Note that you need to provide the fully qualified class name for the listener class.

To add an attachment to Allure report for each step, you can use the `@Attachment` annotation in your test code. You can add this annotation to any test method, and any attachment added using this annotation will be displayed in Allure report for that test.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to add an attachment to Allure report for each step:

```
import io.qameta.allure.Attachment;
import org.openqa.selenium.OutputType;
import org.openqa.selenium.TakesScreenshot;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.testng.Assert;
import org.testng.annotations.AfterClass;
import org.testng.annotations.BeforeClass;
import org.testng.annotations.Test;

public class MyTestClass {
    private WebDriver driver;

    @BeforeClass
    public void setup() {
        // initialize WebDriver
    }

    @AfterClass
    public void teardown() {
        // close WebDriver
    }

    @Test
    public void testFoo() {
        // some test steps here
        attachScreenshot();
        // some more test steps here
        attachScreenshot();
        // some more test steps here
        attachScreenshot();
        Assert.assertTrue(true);
    }

    @Attachment(value = "Screenshot", type = "image/png")
    private byte[] attachScreenshot() {
        return ((TakesScreenshot) driver).getScreenshotAs(OutputType.BYTES);
    }
}
```

In this code, we first import the `@Attachment` annotation from `io.qameta.allure` package which is used to add attachment to Allure report. We also import `OutputType` and `TakesScreenshot` interfaces from `org.openqa.selenium` package to capture the screenshot.

In the `testFoo()` method, we call the `attachScreenshot()` method after each test step to capture a screenshot and attach it to the Allure report using the `@Attachment` annotation. The `value` attribute of the `@Attachment` annotation specifies the attachment name, and the `type` attribute specifies the attachment type (which is 'image/png' in this case for PNG image).

The `attachScreenshot()` method captures the screenshot and returns it as a Byte array. This Byte array is then used by the `@Attachment` annotation to create the attachment.

In Allure report, each attachment added using `@Attachment` annotation will be displayed as a link under the corresponding test step. When the user clicks on the link, the attachment will be displayed in a separate popup window.

In TestNG, `afterInvocation` is a method-level listener that is called after each test method invocation (including configuration methods) regardless of the test result. This listener provides an opportunity to perform some cleanup or post-processing logic after a test method has completed execution.

Here is an example of how the `afterInvocation` method can be used to perform some cleanup logic after each test method invocation:

```
import org.testng.IInvokedMethod;
import org.testng.IInvokedMethodListener;
import org.testng.ITestResult;

public class MyListener implements IInvokedMethodListener {
    public void beforeInvocation(IInvokedMethod method, ITestResult testResult) {
        // Do nothing before test method invocation
    }

    public void afterInvocation(IInvokedMethod method, ITestResult testResult) {
        // Perform cleanup after test method invocation
        System.out.println("Cleaning up after test method: " + method.getTestMethod().getMethodName());
    }
}
```

In this example, we create a custom listener class `MyListener` that implements the `IInvokedMethodListener` interface which has two methods `beforeInvocation()` and `afterInvocation()`. 

The `beforeInvocation()` method is called before each test method invocation and we leave it empty in this example.

The `afterInvocation()` method is called after each test method invocation, regardless of the test result, and we print a message that indicates that some cleanup is being performed.

To use this listener, you can specify it in the TestNG test suite either programmatically or using the XML configuration file:

```
import org.testng.TestListenerAdapter;
import org.testng.TestNG;

public class MyTestRunner {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TestListenerAdapter tla = new TestListenerAdapter();
        TestNG testng = new TestNG();

        testng.setTestClasses(new Class[]{MyTest.class});
        testng.addListener(tla);
        testng.addListener(new MyListener());

        testng.run();
    }
}
```

In this example, we create a custom TestNG test runner `MyTestRunner` that specifies the test classes to be executed as well as the listener that will be used. We add the `MyListener` class as a listener to the TestNG instance that will run the tests.

When the tests are executed, TestNG will call the `beforeInvocation()` method of the listener before each test method invocation and the `afterInvocation()` method of the listener after each test method invocation.
